  "19-7": (
    caption: [Separation of functional complexes of the respiratory chain. The outer mitochondrial membrane is first removed by treatment with the detergent digitonin. Fragments of inner membrane are then obtained by osmotic rupture of the mitochondria, and the fragments are gently dis- solved in a second detergent. The resulting mixture of inner membrane proteins is resolved by ion-exchange chromatography into different com- plexes (I through IV) of the respiratory chain, each with its unique protein composition (see Table 19–3), and the enzyme ATP synthase (sometimes called Complex V). The isolated Complexes I through IV catalyze trans- fers between donors (NADH and succinate), intermediate carriers (Q and cytochrome c), and O2, as shown. In vitro, isolated ATP synthase has only ATP-hydrolyzing (ATPase), not ATP-synthesizing, activity. c19OxidativePhosphorylationAndPhotophosphorylation.indd Page 739 27/09/12 1:33 PM user-F408 c19OxidativePhosphorylationAndPhotophosphorylation.indd Page 739 27/09/12 1:33 PM user-F408 /Users/user-F408/Desktop /Users/user-F408/Desktop 19.1 Electron-Transfer Reactions in Mitochondria 739],
