  "19-18": (
    caption: [ROS formation in mitochondria and mitochondrial defenses. When the rate of electron entry into the respiratory chain and the rate of electron transfer through the chain are mismatched, superoxide radical (•O2 2 ) production increases at Complexes I and III as the partially reduced ubiquinone radical (•Q2) donates an electron to O2. Superoxide acts on aconitase, a 4Fe-4S protein, to release Fe2(cid:2). In the presence of Fe2(cid:2), the Fenton reaction leads to formation of the highly reactive hy- droxyl free radical (•OH). The reactions shown in blue defend the cell against the damaging effects of superoxide. Reduced glutathione (GSH; see Fig. 22–29) donates electrons for the reduction of H2O2 and of the oxidized Cys residues (OSOSO) of enzymes and other proteins, and GSH is regenerated from the oxidized form (GSSG) by reduction with NADPH.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
